{%- comment -%}
  One journal card. Rendered from TWO sources and deliberately shared between them so they can
  never drift apart:

    1. real articles pulled from a Shopify blog  (sections/dev-journal-cards.liquid, blog mode)
    2. hand-authored blocks                      (the same file, fallback mode)

  Every value arrives as a parameter — the snippet reads no `block` and no `section`, so it does
  not care which mode it is in.

  @param {object} [image]        - Shopify image object (article.image or an image_picker value)
  @param {string} [image_alt]    - alt text; the caller resolves the fallback chain
  @param {string} [badge]        - the "Guest Review" / "Insight" pill; omitted when blank
  @param {string} [meta]         - "4 min read ㆍBy Priya s"
  @param {string} [heading]      - card headline (may contain inline HTML in fallback mode)
  @param {number} [heading_level] - 3 by default; the CALLER owns this, because the right level
                                    depends on what sits above the card in the document, not on the
                                    card. Under dev-journal-cards the section's own h2 sits above it,
                                    so 3 is right. On the blog index the page's h1 sits directly
                                    above it and 3 would skip a level, so dev-blog passes 2.
  @param {string} [url]          - where the CTA points
  @param {string} [cta_label]    - CTA text; the whole CTA is omitted when blank
  @param {string} [attrs]        - block.shopify_attributes in fallback mode, blank in blog mode

  @param {string} [sizes_desktop] - the `sizes` expression for ≥769px. NO DEFAULT THAT FITS BOTH:
                                    dev-journal-cards is a fixed 3-up flex row, dev-blog is an
                                    auto-fill grid that steps 3 → 2 → 1. See the media comment.
  @param {number} [ratio_desktop] - CDN crop ratio (w/h) for the ≥769px source
  @param {string} [widths_desktop] - srcset ladder for the ≥769px source
  @param {boolean} [eager]        - true for the one card that can be the LCP element
{%- endcomment -%}

{%- assign h = heading_level | default: 3 -%}

<li class="journal-cards__card" {{ attrs }}>
  <article class="journal-cards__card-inner">
    {%- if image != blank -%}
      {%- comment -%}
        THE CARD IMAGE IS A FIXED-HEIGHT, FLUID-WIDTH `object-fit: cover` BOX — 220px tall on
        desktop, 150px on mobile (--card-image-h / --card-image-h-m). It used to be requested at the
        source's own aspect and left for the browser to crop, which meant paying for pixels that
        were then thrown away. Measured on /blogs/news at 1440 / DPR 2:

          box      412 x 220 CSS  ->  824 x 440 device  =  0.36 Mpx needed
          shipped  1000 x 1435             (the 1000w entry)  =  1.44 Mpx  — 4x
          card-2   743,398 B for that one card

        Passing height + crop moves the crop to the CDN, so an srcset entry is the box, not a tall
        portrait waiting to be trimmed. `image_tag`'s `widths:` scales the height with the width, so
        every entry keeps the ratio (verified in the rendered srcset, same as dev-video-promo-banner).

        TWO SOURCES, because one aspect cannot serve both breakpoints — the box is ~1.9 wide-to-tall
        at 375 and can be as tall as ~1.45 on desktop. A single ratio would have to satisfy the
        taller one and would then over-deliver on mobile, which is the half Lighthouse scores.

        The ratio is the SMALLEST (tallest) box the breakpoint can produce, never the average: with
        `cover`, a source WIDER than the box is trimmed at the sides and its height is what runs
        out first, so anything above the minimum renders upscaled. Mobile bottoms out at 320vw:
        (320 − 32) / 150 = 1.92. The desktop minimum differs per caller, hence the parameter.

        card-2 measured on the CDN, 824x440: 743,398 -> 205,744 B cropped -> ~152,000 B at q75.

        QUALITY IS 54, DOWN FROM 75. The card is the smallest surface this photography appears on —
        412x220 CSS at 2x — so it can carry a lower quality than the article hero, which is the same
        pictures at five times the area.

        The number is measured on the DELIVERED format, and that distinction is the whole point.
        Shopify hands these to the browser as WebP by content negotiation, and WebP's quality curve
        is far flatter than JPEG's — the figure a `format: 'jpg'` probe reports is roughly double the
        real saving. Measured across all three cards at the 840x500 desktop crop, WebP out:

          q75  225,364  <- was      q60  195,322  -13.3%
          q70  215,084   -4.6%      q58  189,626  -15.9%
          q65  202,768  -10.0%      q54  179,157  -20.5%

        So 54, not the 60 that the same -20% would have implied under JPEG. Checked on the rendered
        page at 2x on the tree canopy — fine branches against bright sky, where WebP goes first —
        and it is clean there. All four sources carry the same value; a card must not change
        quality when the viewport crosses a band boundary.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- liquid
        assign ratio_d = ratio_desktop | default: 1.45
        assign widths_d = widths_desktop | default: '320, 420, 520, 640, 760, 880, 1040, 1240, 1480'
        assign sizes_d = sizes_desktop | default: 'calc((100vw - 192px) / 3)'

        assign widths_m = '300, 380, 460, 560, 660, 780, 900, 1040, 1200, 1472' | split: ', '
        assign ratio_m = 1.92

        comment
          UP TO THREE DESKTOP BANDS, all optional, all driven by the caller. This exists because the
          card is a FIXED-HEIGHT, fluid-width cover box: the image height is pinned at 220px while
          the width follows the grid, so the box aspect changes with the viewport and a `w`-descriptor
          srcset — which scales both dimensions together — cannot track it.

          A band's crop ratio has to be its NARROWEST card, because with `cover` a source wider than
          the box runs out of height first and anything above the minimum renders upscaled. So one
          band across the whole desktop range is priced at its worst viewport and carries that crop
          everywhere. Splitting the range lets each band be priced at its own floor.

          Both callers reach the same conclusion from opposite directions:
            dev-blog             grid reflows 3 -> 2 -> 1, so cards get WIDER as the viewport
                                 narrows; its floor recurs at 800 and 1152, hence a split at 1300.
            dev-journal-cards    fixed 3-up that never reflows, so cards get NARROWER — 211px at
                                 820 against a 220px image height is a box taller than it is wide.

          `tablet_max` / `wide_min` are the boundaries; the <source> order below is what makes them
          bind, so they are written narrowest-first and must stay that way.
        endcomment
        assign has_tablet = false
        if ratio_tablet
          assign has_tablet = true
          assign widths_t = widths_tablet | split: ', '
          assign h_t = 1200 | divided_by: ratio_tablet | round
        endif

        assign has_wide = false
        if ratio_wide
          assign has_wide = true
          assign widths_w = widths_wide | split: ', '
          assign h_w = 1600 | divided_by: ratio_wide | round
        endif

        comment
          `quality` is ILLEGAL on a png source — image_url raises "quality can't be used with ext
          png" and the whole srcset renders as an error string. This image is merchant content
          (article.image on the blog index, an image_picker in fallback mode), so the extension is
          not knowable in advance and has to be read off the URL. Forcing format: 'jpg' instead
          would be the other way out, but it flattens alpha, and nothing here can promise a
          merchant's png has none. A png simply keeps the crop and skips the recompression — the
          crop is the larger half of the win anyway (-72% vs the -25% that quality adds).
        endcomment
        assign img_ext = image | image_url: width: 1 | split: '?' | first | split: '.' | last | downcase
        assign can_quality = true
        assign img_png = false
        if img_ext == 'png' or img_ext == 'gif'
          assign can_quality = false
        endif
        if img_ext == 'png'
          assign img_png = true
        endif

        comment
          1500, not the width of any box on the page: `image_tag` DROPS every `widths:` entry
          wider than the base url, silently, so a base of 1000 truncated the ladder at 960 and
          the top three rungs never reached the srcset. The base only ever renders as the `src`
          fallback for a browser without srcset, so it costs nothing to put it above the ladder.
        endcomment
        assign h_d = 1500 | divided_by: ratio_d | round
        assign h_m = 768 | divided_by: ratio_m | round

        if can_quality
          assign src_d = image | image_url: width: 1500, height: h_d, crop: 'center', quality: 54
        elsif img_png
          assign src_d = image | image_url: width: 1500, height: h_d, crop: 'center', format: 'webp', quality: 54
        else
          assign src_d = image | image_url: width: 1500, height: h_d, crop: 'center'
        endif

        comment
          `eager` alone only takes the image out of the lazy queue; it still queues behind every
          other subresource. 'high' is what moves it ahead of them, and it is only honest on the one
          card that can actually be the LCP element — marking them all high is the same as marking
          none. 'auto' is the attribute's own default, so the other cards render unchanged.
        endcomment
        if eager
          assign card_loading = 'eager'
          assign card_priority = 'high'
        else
          assign card_loading = 'lazy'
          assign card_priority = 'auto'
        endif
      -%}
      <div class="journal-cards__media">
        <picture>
          <source
            media="(max-width: 768px)"
            sizes="calc(100vw - 32px)"
            srcset="
              {%- for w in widths_m -%}
                {%- assign wn = w | plus: 0 -%}
                {%- assign hn = wn | divided_by: ratio_m | round -%}
                {%- if can_quality -%}
                  {{ image | image_url: width: wn, height: hn, crop: 'center', quality: 54 }} {{ wn }}w
                {%- elsif img_png -%}
                  {{ image | image_url: width: wn, height: hn, crop: 'center', format: 'webp', quality: 54 }} {{ wn }}w
                {%- else -%}
                  {{ image | image_url: width: wn, height: hn, crop: 'center' }} {{ wn }}w
                {%- endif -%}
                {%- unless forloop.last %}, {% endunless -%}
              {%- endfor -%}
            "
            width="768"
            height="{{ h_m }}"
          >

          {%- if has_tablet -%}
            <source
              media="(max-width: {{ tablet_max | default: 1151 }}px)"
              sizes="{{ sizes_tablet | default: sizes_d }}"
              srcset="
                {%- for w in widths_t -%}
                  {%- assign wn = w | plus: 0 -%}
                  {%- assign hn = wn | divided_by: ratio_tablet | round -%}
                  {%- if can_quality -%}
                    {{ image | image_url: width: wn, height: hn, crop: 'center', quality: 54 }} {{ wn }}w
                  {%- elsif img_png -%}
                    {{ image | image_url: width: wn, height: hn, crop: 'center', format: 'webp', quality: 54 }} {{ wn }}w
                  {%- else -%}
                    {{ image | image_url: width: wn, height: hn, crop: 'center' }} {{ wn }}w
                  {%- endif -%}
                  {%- unless forloop.last %}, {% endunless -%}
                {%- endfor -%}
              "
              width="1200"
              height="{{ h_t }}"
            >
          {%- endif -%}

          {%- comment -%}
            The WIDE band is listed before the <img> but after the narrower sources, because a
            <picture> takes the FIRST <source> whose media matches. Its min-width therefore has to
            sit above tablet_max, and the <img> is left as the fallback for everything in between.
          {%- endcomment -%}
          {%- if has_wide -%}
            <source
              media="(min-width: {{ wide_min | default: 1440 }}px)"
              sizes="{{ sizes_wide | default: sizes_d }}"
              srcset="
                {%- for w in widths_w -%}
                  {%- assign wn = w | plus: 0 -%}
                  {%- assign hn = wn | divided_by: ratio_wide | round -%}
                  {%- if can_quality -%}
                    {{ image | image_url: width: wn, height: hn, crop: 'center', quality: 54 }} {{ wn }}w
                  {%- elsif img_png -%}
                    {{ image | image_url: width: wn, height: hn, crop: 'center', format: 'webp', quality: 54 }} {{ wn }}w
                  {%- else -%}
                    {{ image | image_url: width: wn, height: hn, crop: 'center' }} {{ wn }}w
                  {%- endif -%}
                  {%- unless forloop.last %}, {% endunless -%}
                {%- endfor -%}
              "
              width="1600"
              height="{{ h_w }}"
            >
          {%- endif -%}

          {{
            src_d
            | image_tag:
              loading: card_loading,
              fetchpriority: card_priority,
              widths: widths_d,
              sizes: sizes_d,
              alt: image_alt,
              class: 'journal-cards__image'
          }}
        </picture>

        {%- if badge != blank -%}
          <span class="journal-cards__badge">{{ badge | escape }}</span>
        {%- endif -%}
      </div>
    {%- endif -%}

    <div class="journal-cards__content">
      {%- if meta != blank -%}
        <p class="journal-cards__meta">{{ meta | escape }}</p>
      {%- endif -%}

      {%- if heading != blank -%}
        {%- comment -%}
          NOT escaped: in fallback mode this is an inline_richtext (already-safe HTML from Shopify),
          and in blog mode the caller passes `article.title | escape`. Escaping here would print the
          entities of the former.
        {%- endcomment -%}
        <h{{ h }} class="journal-cards__card-heading">{{ heading }}</h{{ h }}>
      {%- endif -%}

      {%- if cta_label != blank -%}
        {%- assign card_link = url | default: '#' -%}
        <a class="journal-cards__cta dev-btn dev-btn--text" href="{{ card_link }}">
          <span class="journal-cards__cta-label dev-btn__label">{{ cta_label | escape }}</span>
          {%- comment -%}
            Path data verbatim from .figma-assets/journal-cards/cta-icon-arrow-right.svg.
          {%- endcomment -%}
          <svg
            class="journal-cards__cta-icon dev-btn__icon"
            width="24"
            height="24"
            viewBox="99 0 24 24"
            fill="none"
            xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
            aria-hidden="true"
            focusable="false"
          >
            <path d="M116 16L120 12L116 8M120 12L102 12" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.4" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
          </svg>
        </a>
      {%- endif -%}
    </div>
  </article>
</li>
